{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_jessie_ver01/data/sn88076516/0029586395A/1910070101/0730.xml":{"full_text":"H. E. BAIRD, PRES.\nF. H. ROUTIER, CASHIER\nAO Bills Collected Monthly.\nC. D. nw.T.q D. V. BRENNAN\nPublisher\nSubscription Price tLH a Ta\nJULY 1, 1910.\nREFORM LEGISLATION.\nNever has any party in control or\nthe na ional congress finished its\nlabors with greater success tnaa the\npresent republican majority at Wash\nington. The list of reform legislation\nadopted is the greatest landmark in\nthe progressive actions of the re\npublican party since the days of Lin\ncoln. President Taft has left upon\nthe statute books of the nation the\nimprint of a wise, progressive, cour\nageous and sane policy. His admini\nstration has the distinction of doing\nthings a id doing what the people want\ndone.\nIn tLe matter of \"reform\" move\nments lor which President Taft stood\nsponsor, there were many instances\nof Boect ss. Chief in the list of leg\nislation for which the administration\ncontended were the following:\nStriking revision of the railroad\nlaws, including the creation of a com\nmerce court\nAdmitting Arizona and New Mexico\nas separate states.\nGiving to the president unlimited\nauthority to withdraw public lands for\nconservation purposes.\nProviding for publicity of campaign\ncontributions.\nAuthorizing the issue of $20,000,000\nin certificates of indebtedness to com\nplete reclamation projects.\nCreating a bureau of mints.\nExtending the activities of the tar\niff board and appropriating $250,000\nfor its use.\nLooking to the suppression of traf\nfic in \"white slaves.\"\nAuthorizing the entry of the sur\nface of coal lands.\nCresting a commission to consider\neconomies in the administration of\nthe federal government.\nProviding a new tariff system for\nthe PLilippine Islands.\nLegislation which ultimately is ex\npected to give practically prohibition\nCo the Hawaiian Islands.\nNot the least conspicuous acts of\ncongress were the strenuous measures\ntaken by the house of representatives\nto reform its system of conducting\nbusiness that less power might be\nreposed in the speaker and the or\nganization of which lie is the natural\nleader.\nThe speaker was removed from the\ncommutee on rules, which lie had\npreviously been credited with domi\nnating and a new one was adopted\nfor the purpose of preventing pigeon\nholing of bills by committees when\nthey v. ere approved by a majority of\nthe hoase, regardless of party affilia\ntion.\nThe enormous proportion of the\ndemands for legislation which are\npressc.1 upon congress is shown by\nthe fact that since the beginning of\nthe present congress more than 27,\nooo bills have been introduced in the\nboose and more than 9,000 in the sen\nate in addition to hundreds of resolu\ntions on various subjects. This rec\nord, so far as the number of bills is\nconcerned, is without a parallel.\nMore time was consumed in consid\nering the railroad bill than was taken\nby\nall other subjects of legislation.\n{Tills measure not only creates a com\nmerce court, but it embodies authori\nty for a commission to inquire Into\nstock and bond issues of railroads,\nextends the provision for the Inter\nState commerce act to telegraph and\ntelephone companies, and gives to the\nInterstate commerce commission pow-\nJOT\nto postpone increases in rates un\nthe coramision shall hare found\nfbs \u2022proposed\nincrease reasonable,\nf- An act also was passed to compel\nrailroads to furnish: to Hie interstate\ny'-g5\nFI. WHIPPLE, Vtds PRES.\nN. J. HALEY, A. CASHIER\nFirst National Bank\nDevils Lake. N, Dak.\nCapital $75,000\nSurplus $35,000\nDevils Lake Inter-Ocean\nPuMMitd waj Friduy at Devils like, Bamsey\nComity, Nortk Tnlrnt\u00bb,\nOfldsl aper Ramsey Coanty and Devils Lake.\ncommerce commission reports on ac\ncidents, so that congress may be bet\nter informed as to the need of further\nlegislation.\nUnder the withdrawal act the presi\ndent was given almost unlimited pow\ner to withhold lands from settlement\nand to conserve the water power. On\nthe other hand, the act providing for\nthe agricultural entry of the surface\nof coal lands will open to setlement\nat least 60,000,000 acres and at the\nsame time reserve to the government\nthe right to the coal. By providing\nfor the opening of a portion of the\nPine Ridge and the Rosebud Indian\nreservations in South Dakota, more\nthan 2,000,000 acres of agricultural\nlands will be available for homestead\nsettlement.\nPOLITICS AND POLITICIANS.\nThe Socialists of New Hampshire\nhave nominated Asa Warren Drew for\ngovernor.\nGovernor Donaghey of Arkansas will\noppose Senator Jeff Davis for re-elec\ntion.\nMrs. L. R. Gammage, of Palestine,\nTexas, is a candidate for county treas\nurer.\nIt is reported in Washington that\nSenator Tillman of South Carolina in\ntends to retire from public life at the\nend of his present term in the senate.\nFormer Governor Frank Brown of\nMaryland has formally announced that\nhe would be a candidate for the Demo\ncratic gubernational nomination next\nyear.\nA recent decision of the Oklahoma\nsupreme court renders it certain that\nthe woman suffrage question will be\nvoted on at the regular election in\nthat state next fall.\nDemocrats of Wisconsin have decid\ned to hold their state convention in\nMilwaukee on July 12 to adopt a plat\nform and make other arrangements\nfor the coming campaign.\nWilliam Brice Cumberland, a drug\ngist of St. Louis, has entered the race\nfor the Democratic nomination for\nUnited States Senator from Missouri to\nsucceed Senator Warner.\nCivic bodies in Pittsburg, Scran ton\nand other Pennsylvania cities will en\ndeavor to make the adoption of the\ncommission form of municipal govern\nment an issue in the state campaign\nthis year.\nThe Socialists of Nebraska are plan\nning this year to nominate a full state\nticket, candidates for United States\nsenator and congressmen and candi\ndates for the state legislature in a\nmajority of the districts.\nEverett J. Lake, the old Harvard\nfootball player, and Charles A Good\nwin, a prominent Tale graduate, are\nrunning a bard race for the Republican\nnomination for governor of Connecti\ncut this year.\nSenator Clapp of Minnesota, Dolli\nver and Cummins of Iowa, La Follette\nof Wisconsin, Borah of Idaho and\nBristow of Kansas have promised to\nspeak in the state of Washington this\nfall in support of Representative\nMiles Polndexter, the progressive Re\npublican candidate for United States\nsenator.\nIn connection with the boom of Col\nlector Loeb for governor of New York,\nit is reported ttiat the only collector\nof the port of New York nominated\nfor governor in the last twenty-five\nyears was Representative J. Sloat Fas\nsett, who was nominated in 1891 and\ndefeated by Roswell P. Flower.\nLeading Republicans of northern\nAlabama are advocating the nomina\ntion af Amos Goodhue, a prominent\nlawyer of Gadsden, as the Republi\ncan candidate for governor of Alabama\nto oppose the Democratic nominee,\nColonel Ehnmett O'Neal, of Florence\nMr. Goodhue is one of the foremost\nprohibitionists in the state\nTHE MAN WHO KNOWS IT CAN'T\nBE DONE.\n(By Herbert Kaufman.)\nHe counts the risk, not the reward.\nHe shrinks before he thinks\u2014quits be\nfore he hits\u2014succumbs to fright be\nfore he makes his fight.\nHis band is always on the reverse\nlever\u2014bis determination runs in die\nwrong direction. His imagination digs\nditches all iteig tte road np|M|ls\nbarriers at every .stage -of \"tke^qr.'^- .j:\nHe's a beac in the market of pro*\ngress\u2014be beta against every united\nissue. Sbow him a pian and hell in\n.variably prove that \"it can't be doae.'\nHe's a hnman cloud continually obs\ncuring the silver lining: of the future.\nHe deities himself the benefit of the\ndoubt and doubts the benefit of any\nthing he doubts. He's not an actor,\nbut a sneering audience\u2014be doesn't\nperform he merely watches.\nHe dampens enthusiasm\u2014ridicules\nInspiration jeers at daring, and mea\nsures all men and manners and\nmethods by the standard of his own\npuny personality.\nHe belongs to no particular period\nor class. The world has known, his\npromise to detect the adulteration in\nthe king's crown.\nIn a later generation they were cer\ntain that Carthage could never be\nconquered. His forbears hooted at the\nridiculous idea of the \"Italian idiot,'\nColumbus.\nHis grandfather would have con\ndemned Fulton to a paddle cell\u2014his\nfather tapped his forehead and smiled\nknowingly when Bell proposed to send\nhis words a hundred miles.\nFive years ago, he himself wagered\nthat no man would ever wing his way\nfrom New York to Philadelphia, min\nute to minute with the Limited Ex\npress\u2014just as ten years before, he\nroared with mirth at the notion of a\ntroUey ride on the ooze of the Hud\nson.\nDon't let him annoy you\u2014he isn't\nreally complete. He's an Inferior prod\nuct\u2014a \"second.\" Nature neglected to\ngive him a backbone\u2014she forgot to\nfilnish his brain\u2014his mind has no\nsparking plug\u2014he can't start\u2014be\nmust be towed along.\nDon't calculate upon his capability\n\u2014be isn't intelligent\u2014he's simply a\nman parrot\u2014he can only reproduce\nwhat he has beard or seen.\nHe isn't fit for responsibilities\u2014he's\nminus pluck, and can't meet an emerg\nency.\nSet him at a machine which will do\nits own thinking\u2014stick him in front\nof a ledger and let him copy figures.\nGive him a duty which involves no\noriginality. Supply him with a book\nof rales\u2014he can't make his Own.\nTeach him what to do. He's too\nignorant to manage himself.\nKeep him in the ranks\u2014he can't\nlead\u2014only fearless men may be cap\ntains. The yellow streak and the\nshoulder strap are not fit companions.\nIn the eyes of a coward, the cause\nis always lost\u2014in the eyes of the\nquitter, the task a failure befoffcit\nstarts. Shove him to the rear\u2014the\npath of civilization must be kept clear\nfor the barve.\nTHE FULFILLMENT OF PROPH\nECY.\nIt is always interesting to delve in\nthe history of the past That there\nwere prophets as well as giants in\nthose days is apparent from a per\nusal of the utterances of men prom\ninent in affairs in the long ago. Roger\nBacon lived something like 600 years\nago. He was a philosopher of the old\nschool and while bis facilities for in\nvestigation and research may not have\nbeen anything like what are available\nin these days yet he studied out many\nscientific truths, applied them in his\ncrude way and evolved many features\nthat afforded a ground work for in\nvestigation in after years. Many of\nthe modern sciences owe their founda\ntion to his investigation and genius.\nHe was not only a scientist but a\nprophet as well. He had a vision of\ngreat steamships, automobiles and\nairships.\nAn old English book printed four\nhundred or so years ago records the\nfollowing conversation as having oc\ncurred with Bacon:\n\"Fryer Bacon answered, Your grace\nsaith well but let mee -(under correc\ntion) tell you, that are oftentimes\ndoth those things that are impossible\nto armies, which I will make good in\nsome few examples. I will speak\nonely of things performed by art and\nnature wherein shall be nothing mag\nical: and first by the figuration of art,\nthere may be made instruments of nav\nigation without men to row in them,\nas great ships to brooke the sea, only\nwith one man to 8 tee re them, and they\nshall sayle far more swiftly than if\nthey were full of men: also chariots\nthat shall move with an unspeakable\nforce, without any living creature to\nstirre them. Likewise, an instrument\nmay be made to fly with all, if one\nsit In the midst of the Instrument,\nand doe turne an engine, by which the\nwings being artificially composed,\nmay beat ayre after the manner of a\nflying bird.\"\nTHE RAILROAD 8ITUATI0N.\nOne billion dollars will be needed\nby the railroads of the United States\nfor extensions and improvements with\nin the next twelve months, accord\ning to the most conservative estimates.\nUnless rates are advanced to a point\nthat will permit a material increase in\nnet earnings it wilt not be possible to\nJtlTh&U\nraise so great iqm..\"\nWithout 41W\nimprovements -'the' lidlttoads cannot'\nhandle any marked increase in\nfie andtherlac)t* oi transportation\nfacilities win irender Impossible any\nreturn of prosperity. This Is the rate\nsituation as Summed up by a railway\nfinancial officer.\nIn 1908, the total capital of the rail\nroads of the United States was $17,\n234,886^15, as compared with -$11,585,\n069,036 In 1898, an Increase of $5,649,\n817,179, or an average of $564,981,717\nper year. But the annual Increase was\nmost sapid In the closing years of the\nperiod, being $1,030,349,026 In 1906,\n$907,864412 in 1907 and $733,473,146 In\nthe dull year of 1908.\nA study of financial publications\nemphasises the increasing difficulty of\nraising money for railroad uses. Rail\nroad bonds which yielded Interest at\nthe average rate of 4.97 per cent in\n1885 and 4.21 per cent in 1898 gave\nonly an average return of 3.88 per cent\nin 1908. The outlook for the stock\nholder is even more discouraging, for\nthe ton mile freight rate which was\n.977 in 1888 had shrunk to .758 In 1898\nand to .765 in 1908. The average Tate\nper passenger per mile dwindled from\n2.246 in 1888 to 1.994 in 1898 and 1.950\ncents in 1908.\nRoosevelt received a great ovation\nin New York upon his return from his\ntrip ahroad. No such a demonstration\nwas ever before known in this country.\nRoosevelt is the greatest man in the\nentire world. There Is something in\nhis makeup that makes him a conspi\ncuous figure even though he seeks\nseclusion and obscurity. When he\nburied himself in the wilds of Africa\nthe newspapers of the country kept\nin close touch with his every move\nment and even the Bavage tribes of\nthat country realized that there was\namong them a man of more than or\ndinary genius. His addresses in Egy\npt and in Europe were of world-wide\nimport and he attracted more atten\ntion from rulers and from the com\nmon people than any American who\nhas ever set foot on foreign shores.\nHis place in the United States is uni\nque. A private citizen and yet the\nmost potent factor in the affairs of the\ncountry that exists. His opinion upon\nmatters of public moment carries\nmore weight than does the opinion of\nany other American whatever bis offi\ncial position may be... Roosevelt Is in\na class by himself.\nPaine, the great fireworks manufact\nurer, says that the agitation for a \"safe\nand sane Fourth of July has greatly\ninjured 'his business. He declares that\nthe incentive to invent and put upon\nthe market new explosives hag been\nsuppressed\u2014strangled, we believe is\nthe word he uses. It may be that Mr.\nPaine's business has been injured but\nbetter that than the loss of life and\nlimb occasioned by the recklessness of\nthe past.\nFAINT HEART AND THE STEAM\nROLLER.\nThere is an old saying that faint\nheart never won fair lady. That an\ncient law might well have Included\nother objects of men's efforts, besides\nlovely woman. Nothing surrenders\neasily to the man with a white-liver\nwhether it be love, war, business, or\npolitics. It is the stout heart that\nwins the day and makes a hopeless\ncontest the forerunner of victory.\nIn politics Mr. \"Faint Heart\" is the\ncommonest sight we see. He is al\nways ready to talk reforms but never\nrieady to work reform. His good in\ntentions melt before opposition like\nsnow before the warm April sun. Gen\nerally there are two things which pre\nvent Mr. \"Faint Heart\" from becom\ning a valuable citizen. Either he or\nhis friends are interested in some\npretty graft which reform would in\njure or, the friends of graft, com\nbined with honest citizens misled by\nfalse statements, seemed so over\nwhelmingly strong that Mr. \"Faint\nHeart\" fears to be on the losing side.\nIn either case he is a useless, often\nharmful member of society. He is the\noriginal \"fraid cat\" of our free in\nstitutions.\nThe mistake which the faint heart\ned man makes Is In thinking that the\ngrafters can not be beaten. They\nThey are never so near to a beating\nas when they appear the strongest\nMoreover no man ever won their re\nspect by fearing them. Fight the\ngrafter, the man who wants to break\nthe law, do It sincerely, and do it fear\nlessly, and he will respect you more\nthan he will his fellow pirates. There\nIs nothing lasting to be gained by run\nning away from the steam roller. If\nft\nflattens you out, dust off your jeans,\npunch the dent out of your hat, and\ncut another shlllala. There is always\na turn In the lane sometime. Per\nhaps It will be on the morrow.\nDon't talk so much about your an\ncestors, but try to so act and do that\nyour grand-children will be proud of\ntheirs.\nDo not trample on the who Is\ndown. No one gets so low but Hmt\nhis good will may be of use to you\nsome day.\n4*\n4. TOKIO 4.\n\u2022FR 4\u00bb\n4* 4* 4* 4* 4*\n(By Special Correspondent.)\nAlex DeMars is on the sick list.\nC. D. Mills was at home to vote Wed\nnesday.\nAlbert Jaqua was at Devils Lake on\nbusiness this week.\nHerb Baitson and family are camp\ning at Chautauqua.\nC. D. Graves was at Devils Lake on\nbusiness Wednesday.\nThe crops in this vicinity are in\nvery poor condition.\nIgnatius Court was at Fort Totten\non business Wednesday.\nC. Smeallie was a Devils Lake visit\nor the first of the week.\nQuite a number of people from this\nvicinity were at Chautauqua Sunday.\nFred Long has \"a contract for digging\nwells for Victor Ruth and Albert\nJaqua.\nC. D. Graves and Burt Jaqua have\nfinished the grade work of Tokio, and\ndid an excellent job.\nD. G. Talley and Attorney Buttz\nwere at Tokio Wednesday looking\nafter political matters.\nMr. Peter Regan from Ramsey coun\nty has rented nine fourtles from Frank\nCockburn of Devils Lake and has about\ntwenty-five head of horses at work\nbreaking it up.\nAt this writing the primary election\nis on and votes are coming in slow In\nWoodlake township. The officers of\nelection are Henry Doyle, inspector\nVictor Ruth and C. D. Mills, judges\nWade Brown and D. R. Chase, clerks.\nThe New York Cash Store Is pre\nparing for the largest fall trade. When\ncrops are poor our trade increases\nmost If you must consider the value\nof a dollar you are sure to spend it at\nthe New York Cash Store.\n\"ir-m-\nfi\nThe prediction for tomorrow is\nwarmer, why should die children\ngo and tuffer in this heat when\nyou can get a muslin Underwaist\nfor 25c. They are superior to die\nknit waists, wear better fit bettor\nand are better than any other kind.\nWe have them in all sizes.\nThe price is only 25 cents\nRODENBACH MUNDT\nTHE NEW DEPARTMENT STORE\nYou Will Need\nA New Outfit\nFor the Fourth of July\nWe can supply it. Inspect our\nstock before buying. See our\nshowing of the late styles and\nfabrics in CLOTHING.\nNew styles in Straw and\nPanama Hats.\nShoes and Oxfords in all\nleathers.\nSummer Underwear of all\ndescriptions.\nWHITE HENDERSON\nOne Pnce Clothiers and Furnishers\nStores at DEVILS LAKE and JAMESTOWN, N. D.\nlitfnte\nPerpetual Motion.\nLittle Jimmy bad arrived at the\nquestioning age. He had just made an\nInquiry concerning perpetual motion\nof his father.\n\"No,\" said his father \"nobody has\never discovered perpetual motion yet\"\nBut Jimmy was not qnite satisfied.\n\"What is perpetual motion like, dad?\"\nhe asked next\nHis father thought a moment. **Why,\nifs pretty hard to say, Jimmy,\" be re\nplied, \"but it's something that keeps\ngoing and going forever. Here to an\nIllustration. I once saw a woman In a\ntrain who had put on her gloves. She\nthen tried to button her right hand\nglove, but she found that she must\ntake off her left hand glove to doso.\nShe took It off and buttoned tlfa right7\nhand glove. Then she saw that Inor\nder to button her left hand glove ate\nmust take off her right hand glove,\nwhich she did. Then she pat on hat,.\nleft hand glove, buttoned it and-put\non the right band one again. But-Cbe\ncouldn't bntton her right hand glove\nwith her left hand glove on, so she\ntook off\u2014 That. Jimmy,\" be said after\na pause for breath, 'is what perpetual 4\nmotion would be like if yon could get\nit\"\nA Remarkable Dinner Service.\nThe remarkable dinner service m&de\nby Joslah Wedgwood for the Russian\nempress, Catherine II., in 1774 consists\nof 962 pieces, and. on each piece is\npainted a different view. The body Is\nof a pale brimstone color, and\nviews are painted in a rich mulbeny\npurple. As the service was intended\nto be used at the palace of \u00a3a Gre\nnouilllere (meaning marshy place full\nof frogs), each piece also bears a\ngreen frog within a shield on the rim\nThe views represent British ruined\ncastles, abbeys, parks, bridges, towers,\netc. Several pieces are decorated with\nviews of Hampstead. and there are\nenstard cups with views of Richmond\nand sauce boats with the scenery: of\nWindsor park. In many cases\nviews are the only pictorial records\nleft of the old buildings. Altogether\nthere are 1,282 views painted on tb\u00bb\n952 pieces.\u2014Connoisseur.","height":"26820","width":"18480"}}
